ts, the victims of HIV/AIDS and "natural" disasters.Missing Bodies presents a call for a new, engaged way of seeing and recovering bodies in a world that routinely, often strategically,obscures or erases them. It poses difficult, even startling questions: Why did it take so long for the United States media to begin telling stories about the "falling bodies" of 9/11? Why has the United States government refused to allow photographs or filming of flag-draped coffins carrying the bodies of soldiers who are dying in Iraq? Why are the bodies of girls and women so relentlessly sexualized? By examining the cultural politics at work in such disappearances and inclusions of the physical body the authors show how the social, medical and economic consequences of visibility can reward or undermine privilege in society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aBody image. 0aEquality. 0aHuman body (Philosophy). 0aMasculinity. 0aMortality. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aCasper.  aJean.  aLisa.  aMonica.  aMoore.  abody.  acentury.  aerasures.  aexplore.  amanipulations.  asurveillance.  atwenty-first.  avisibility.1 aMoore, Lisa Jean, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978081471678640uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814772980.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814772980423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814772980/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE